<dl id="n08180h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08180h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08180h"> 180(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Fianna standing army rise v / Carbery s. of Cormac / battle of Gavra (Skreen) / falls destroyed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Standing armies have always been a danger to the power which should control them, and especially so in early phases of development. The Fianna became a rival power to the throne, and in the day of Cormac&apos;s son Carbery the issue was fought out in a desperate battle at Gowra, now the Hill of Skreen, near Tara, where Carbery fell, but the Fianna were destroyed. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 15</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A line connects &lsquo;Fianna&rsquo; with &lsquo;destroyed&rsquo;. and &lsquo;Carbery&rsquo; to &lsquo;falls&rsquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
